The European Council adopted its position or “general approach” on the Chips Act on Dec. 1 2022. This marks a major milestone in Europe’s efforts to catch up with other regions in the production of semiconductors and improve its resilience to supply chain disruptions.

On February 8 2022 the European Commission submitted to the European Parliament and the Council a proposal for a regulation establishing a framework of measures to strengthen Europe’s semiconductor ecosystem. The European Chips Act is set to mobilize €43 billion in public and private funding for the semiconductor industry with the ambition to double the EU’s current share of global chip production to 20% in 2030.

In a statement semiconductor industry association SEMI celebrated the progress on the European Chips Act by the European Council and reiterated its support for an early start to negotiations in 2023.

“The future for Europe as a region of semiconductor manufacturing excellence is brimming with possibility” commented Laith Altimime president of SEMI Europe. “The adoption of the European Council’s general approach marks a critical step in passage of the European Chips Act as a landmark initiative for our industry.”

Amended propositions

On Nov. 25 the Council presented its “Regulation establishing a framework of measures for strengthening Europe’s semiconductor ecosystem (Chips Act) – General approach”. The Council indeed amended several provisions of the Commission’s proposal to take into account the requests of delegations during the discussions at working group level to improve the clarity and feasibility of the proposal and to ensure legal certainty.

As listed in the 105-page document the Council’s proposed changes concerned the following 10 issues:

the definition of “first-of-a-kind” semiconductor manufacturing facility to clarify that the qualifying element could be innovation in many different dimensions;

the formulation of the general and operational objectives and the content of the Chips for Europe Initiative as well as the specification of research and innovation activities and of capacity building activities;

the harmonizing component of the Chips Act and the objective of improving the functioning of the internal market;

the establishment of a European network of competence centers in semiconductors integration technologies and system design;

the requirements to be met by Integrated Production Facilities and Open EU Foundries notably as regards positive spill-over effects on the Union’s semiconductor value chain;

the role of Member States through the European Semiconductor Board in the decision on the status of Integrated Production Facility or Open EU Foundry including in the case of a repeal;

the possibility to derogate from environmental procedures in the planning construction and operation of Integrated Production Facilities or Open EU Foundries considered to be of “overriding public interest”;

the design of mandatory information requests during a crisis stage to be carried out by the Commission including safeguards to ensure their proportionality and security interests;

the scope and implementation of the emergency toolbox as regards the list of critical sectors and the instruments of priority rated orders and common purchasing and the provision of a Council implementing act to trigger a crisis stage;

the enforcement of information and notification obligations and of the compliance with priority rated orders through fines and penalties.

European Chips Infrastructure Consortium

The Chips Act regulation suggested a new legal entity the European Chips Infrastructure Consortium (ECIC) to structure legal relationships between private and public members and to act as an interface for the implementation of actions.

The Council has proposed further clarification on the voluntary nature of establishing an ECIC on its openness to different legal forms of cooperation and other participants and on its rules for the selection of proposals for funding that should not be based on a specific legal form of cooperation.

What’s next?

Now that the Council has adopted its position the European Parliament’s Committee on Industry Research and Energy (ITRE) is expected to vote on the European Union Chips Act Report in January 2023.

Once approved the Committee will submit the text to plenary for adoption. The vote in plenary is scheduled in February 2023. The text would constitute the European Parliament’s negotiating position and marks the last step before the start of trialogue negotiations among the European Commission Parliament and Council SEMI said.

